WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.700
Welcome back. In this lesson, we will try using both x64dbg and Ghidra together to solve a crackme.

00:00:07.700 --> 00:00:32.220
me. But before we do that, let's take a snapshot of our Ghidra MCP setup. Then, we start our

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:44.620
Windows 11 virtual machine. We see that openclaw gateway is starting. We also open telegram.

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:48.420
Clear the history first if necessary

00:00:48.420 --> 00:00:59.660
Then, type the command slash new to start a fresh session so that we get new context

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:03.680
This time, we will use the simple serial crack me

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:08.850
We run it and see how it behaves

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:24.800
Then, we start Ghidra

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:36.850
Drag simple serial into Ghidra

00:01:36.850 --> 00:02:00.170
Then, drag it into the dragon icon to begin analysis

00:02:00.170 --> 00:02:23.770
Let's run x32dbg as administrator

00:02:23.770 --> 00:02:28.460
Then open the simple serial crack me

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:43.660
Click on the log tab to confirm that the MCP server is listening

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:54.450
Rearrange the windows side by side

00:02:54.450 --> 00:03:03.230
Go back to telegram and give openClaw your instructions

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:10.940
Ask it to check if it can connect to both x64dbg and also Ghidra

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:16.380
Remind it to refer to its memory since it has done this before

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:29.960
OpenClaw is now checking both MCP connections

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:37.700
It tells me that it can connect to x64 DBG but fails to connect to Ghidra

00:03:37.700 --> 00:03:43.890
It seems I have forgotten to start the Ghidra bridge

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:45.570
Let's do that now

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:53.180
Go to the Ghidra MCP folder and activate your Python environment

00:03:53.180 --> 00:04:10.740
Then run the bridge script

00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:38.040
Confirm that it has started, then go back to Telegram and inform OpenClaw and ask it to try again.

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:47.320
OpenClaw confirms it can now connect to Ghidra.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:05:07.870
Now, we give our instructions to ask it to analyze the Crackme.

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:10.870
You should give as much details as you can.

00:05:10.870 --> 00:05:17.010
The more details, the better it can do its job.

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:45.300
We take another look at the simple serial CrackMe to see its behavior.

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:57.940
and we then inform OpenClaw what we find.

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:03.820
Tell it the strings and messages you see.

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:07.820
Ask it to use both x64DBG and Ghidra together

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:23.620
so that the insights from one tool can help with the other.

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:26.620
OpenClaw is now tracing the message strings.

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:35.060
It successfully found the control flow logic

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:37.060
which shows the error message.

00:06:37.060 --> 00:07:36.060
It also suggests going deeper

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:38.060
and we confirm doing that.

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:55.380
After digging deeper, it got more insights where the serial key might be located.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:27.980
It suggested running the binary after it has set some breakpoints.

00:08:47.090 --> 00:09:04.260
I asked if I should run the binary and it replies yes and gives further instructions.

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:31.380
I enter some wrong serial number and inform OpenClaw that it has hit a breakpoint.

00:09:57.700 --> 00:10:00.780
OpenClaw says it is reading the live arguments.

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:13.550
It then asked me to give it a screenshot of the stack.

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:54.080
So I used the snipping tool to take a screenshot of the stack and pasted it into Telegram.

00:11:04.130 --> 00:11:07.570
Then informed OpenClaw that I have sent it a screenshot.

00:11:13.890 --> 00:11:20.690
It asked me to press F7 to step into each line until it reaches a specific EIP address.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.760
So I will try that now.

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:45.820
After trying this for a while, I got lost.

00:11:45.820 --> 00:12:06.590
So, I told OpenClaw I missed it and asked to retry again.

00:12:06.590 --> 00:12:29.280
OpenClaw replies telling me to rerun the binary and re-enter the serial key.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:35.140
I did that and this time it hits the correct breakpoint that OpenClaw is looking for.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:53.740
I inform OpenClaw.

00:12:53.740 --> 00:13:15.620
I then took a screenshot of the stack and pasted it into Telegram.

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:35.690
OpenClaw then replies that the correct serial is ABC-123456.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:58.730
We then run simple serial and key it in, and it is correct.

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:24.020
I then ask OpenClaw if it could have used Ghidra to solve it as well.

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:51.940
It replies that Ghidra also shows the same serial.

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:58.680
It then shows me the insights it got from Ghidra.

00:14:58.680 --> 00:15:04.620
So this is how we could use both x64 DBG and Ghidra together, where the insights from one

00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:08.080
tool could be used to help the other tool.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:10.400
That's all for this video.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:11.240
Thanks for watching.

